commentBody:
@Ciptir 

Mx. doesn't stand for anything, it's just an alternative for the r/rs/s. Mr wouldn't be correct because (presumably) they told the NYT to use Mx. 

As someone who's also some flavor of nonbinary, he most likely uses Mx. to highlight their trans identity

@Vaer 

I gave up, frustrated, sometime before 1am to get to the column. In addition to refreshing the web page multiple times, I also tried manually typing in the URL, then modifying an existing, functioning one for another date, etc. 

How were you able to get to the column despite it being down? Would love to know for the (sadly) next time...

@G 
Open up the Wordplay column of the previous day's puzzle.  Scroll way, way down almost to the bottom where it says More in Wordplay.   That's a link, but also below that link while you are still in the column are direct links to each of the latest Wordplay columns, including the one you can't access because the link where you normally go is broken.  
I did that from memory, so hopefully got most of the directions correct. But the main thing is to scroll down to the bottom of a Wordplay column you can access and use what's down there.

@William James 
For the record, several of her books ARE on my bookshelf, unread. I just have to read all the other books on my bookshelf before I get to hers...

The list only gets longer.

@Andrzej 

First of all, mega props to you.  I speak only one language, and I'm in awe of anyone who does a crossword puzzle in their non-native language.

As far as this puzzle goes, it seems as though you had enough knowledge to get it if you had a little more patience.  When you look things up before trying to draw on your intuition, you aren't strengthening that particular talent.  You may not have the time or desire to do that, so as long as you're enjoying yourself, that's fine.  We're all here for different reasons.

@Jess

To add: E__N, O_S and UN_S were not previously known to me and were difficult for me to guess from the way they were clued, which left TAR BA__ unsolvable without looking it up. 

If anyone else struggled similarly with those same words and managed to figure things out without the help of Google, would appreciate hearing your thought process to help me with future puzzles 🙂

@Reuben 

I don't think OY is a variant of OI (I picture Roy Kent of "Ted Lasso" here); in fact, I think OI is probably more likely related to HEY, which is basically how it's used.

OY is Yiddish in origin, well known where Jewish influence is strong (i.e. New York and the US Northeast in general), and is definitely a shortening of "OY vey", which itself is short for "OY vey iz mir", which means  "Oh, woe is me".

@Steve L 
I was reminded that first day of school time was here because in the coverage of yesterday's California earthquake, they showed footage of LA high-schoolers being evacuated onto their school's athletic field.  
I was a little surprised that they started this early in LA.

@Dave C I mean name is kind of familiar to my ear I think, but never read one book of hers in school or out, but have read other powerful works of literature.

Truth is that sometimes there's too much knowledge and not enough time.

Because of that I never would use a condescending phrase of "I guess you get a pass".

@dizzyspins 

I had a different exposure to TARBABY (Brer Rabbit and the Tarbaby) and actually never heard this used as a slur (though plenty of other words or phrases were in use)...but I don't disbelieve you for a minute.
  Toni Morrison had a reason for her title, and therefore it belongs in the puzzle dedicated to her and her works.

@Rosalind Mitchell 
Hail, fellow OU alumnus. I too got 35A, plus 42A on my BA LIT course. Happy days, cramming studying in between school/nursery runs with the kids. It was the only time of the day I could be ‘me’ instead of Mum.
15A familiar from Spelling Bee, but only discovered what it is today.

@Helen Wright 

"Sugarman done fly away"

Still sticks with me. If anybody recognises it they will know and if they don't they won't. And I still soft-boil an egg that way after all that time! (A319, York Summer School, 1992)

@Nitpicker 
I'm not familiar with the author and found this puzzle to be on the tougher side (for a Tuesday). Took me just over 55 minutes!

I did enjoy it, though ...

@AM 

Thanks for the reminder about all those lovely bits of this lovely puzzle! 

I had noticed the shooting stars, and the crossing of AROUSE and DESIRE (but missed TENDER). In all my excitement over the theme fill, and subsequent discussion of Morrison in the comments, beautiful elements like those had dropped from view for me.
